Raw dev notes -- Diving deep into shipping data and Angular mysteries

Okay, so this past week or so has been a whirlwind on the shipping tracking dashboard project. The whole point of this thing is to give us a clear, real-time view into all our shipments, flagging anything that's going wrong before it becomes a huge problem. Think of it as a mission control for packages, making sure things get where they need to be on time and helping us understand why they don't.

What's been happening? A lot, actually. The big win was getting a direct REST API path hooked up. This means we're pulling in much more reliable, up-to-the-minute data, which is crucial for everything else. Building on that, I finally got the data-driven logic for "stuck" shipments and SLA detection working. It's not just a simple timer; it's looking at a bunch of different data points to figure out if a package is genuinely delayed or just in a normal transit phase. Seeing that light up when a shipment actually *is* stuck feels like a small victory every time.

Then, this week, I pushed out the new insights dashboard. This is where all that raw data and detection logic really shines, giving a visual overview of what's happening across the board. Plus, I managed to squeeze in a billing audit feature, which was a bit of a beast to get right, but super important for the business side. And, of course, a good old codebase reorg and docs cleanup happened – because who doesn't love a tidy house?

But man, it wasn't all smooth sailing. The absolute biggest headache, and honestly, the most surprising thing, was the "angular bundle reverse-engineering pipeline" chore. I had to dig deep into an existing Angular frontend, basically trying to understand its internal workings and data flows without any proper source code or documentation. It felt like being a digital archaeologist, sifting through minified JavaScript to piece together what was going on. There were moments I wanted to pull my hair out, just staring at obfuscated variable names, trying to guess their purpose. It was a proper rabbit hole, and I spent way more time on it than I expected. It really highlighted the challenges of working with legacy systems or integrating with components where you don't have full control or visibility.

Honestly, after that Angular deep dive, getting the new features like the insights dashboard and billing audit out felt incredibly satisfying. It's a good reminder that sometimes you have to do the grunt work, the detective work, to enable the cool, impactful stuff. It felt good to connect the dots from raw, messy data to actionable insights and a tangible product feature. It's a testament to persistence, I guess, and not being afraid to get your hands dirty with the less glamorous parts of development.

Next up: Performance optimizations and more detailed reporting.
